<subSubSection id="C34D47CEFFFCC87FFF0DBE6DFA53FBAF" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BE81445FFFCC87FFF0DBE6DFA53FBAF" blockId="2.[151,1436,1078,1249]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">
<emphasis id="B923C857FFFCC87FFF0DBE6DFED9FB8A" bold="true" box="[151,264,1078,1104]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. This species can be recognised by the presence of setulae at lower posterior part of anepimeron and on katepimeron. The 
<specimenCount id="9D51DFCCFFFCC87FFEA4BE00FE82FBAF" box="[318,339,1115,1141]" pageId="2" pageNumber="357" type="male">♂</specimenCount>
has tergite 6 with abundant long curled setae enclosing the abdominal tip like a “basket” (
<figureCitation id="136C08C0FFFCC87FFAABBE01FAA0FBAF" box="[1329,1393,1114,1141]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–2" captionStartId="3.[151,262,1940,1964]" captionTargetBox="[303,1285,179,1914]" captionTargetId="figure-17@3.[303,1285,179,1914]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–2. Drymeia caucasica (Schnabl), ♂ habitus. 1. Lateral view. 2. Dorsal view. Scale-line 1 mm. (Georgia, SE of Kazbegi, meadows/scree, 1900–1950 m, 5.vii.1983.)" figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6538203" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6538203/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="357">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
